Checklist Comments: Traveled from NE corner along hell gate and stopped checklist after abandoned golf driving range. Driving range was spectacular: abundant sparrows (5 species) all actively foraging and calling. Water was a little slower than expected but got to see a kestrel make a very lazy pass at a chickadee.

A really delightful winter day at Randall’s. Went from NE corner along kill and then finished at old golf range. Plentiful flocks of geese, gulls and shovelers along the NE corner. Finally made some progress on my gull ID by picking out an immature GBBG from afar. Highlight of the day was far and away the lifer Greater Scaup hanging out with an equally cute bufflehead in the western end of the Bronx kill. We ended up calling things short as the wind and chill were starting to get to us, but not before we had sparrow redemption with confident sightings of field sparrows (which we had mistaken a chipping sparrow for on our last visit). I had been very much hoping for an American tree sparrow too which all too briefly popped out at the very end. Only major dip was on the local kestrel(s) which we had hopped to catch up with.

Felt like kind of a slow day based on the prime weather conditions, but also didn’t get to complete a loop of the island either. Highlights were the gregarious Fish Crows making mischief across the ballfields, haranguing starlings and poking into the lights on the fields. Also it was wonderful to get close looks at the Warbling Vireos in the freshwater wetlands.
Walked from southeast corner to pedestrian bridge. Pretty quiet, but great FOS Brant sighting and possibly the largest RTHA we’ve ever seen.

Sadly there also were a large number of injured birds too, mostly with injured or missing legs. Dipped on the avocet but got to see plenty of other outstanding birds. Conditions were muddy but still easily passable.

Checklist Comments: A really delightful winter day at Randall’s. Went from NE corner along kill and then finished at old golf range. Plentiful flocks of geese, gulls and shovelers along the NE corner. Finally made some progress on my gull ID by picking out an immature GBBG from afar. Highlight of the day was far and away the lifer Greater Scaup hanging out with an equally cute bufflehead in the western end of the Bronx kill. We ended up calling things short as the wind and chill were starting to get to us, but not before we had sparrow redemption with confident sightings of field sparrows (which we had mistaken a chipping sparrow for on our last visit). I had been very much hoping for an American tree sparrow too which all too briefly popped out at the very end. Only major dip was on the local kestrel(s) which we had hopped to catch up with.

Probably gotta be the best checklist and best trip we’ve done on the AT. Conditions were arguably poor, but I have to say a rainy hike has its own magic. I’ve never experienced the trail more birdy than this. From the moment we started to when we stopped we were surrounded by constant song and activity. The rain did nothing to dampen the songs and busy activity of summer. Willow flycatchers, yellow warblers and red-winged blackbirds were abundant along the boardwalk. An eastern phoebe pair again has set up shop at the end of the boardwalk. The woods were positively awash with song. The Ovenbird count is almost certainly a severe undercount as is the Veery and Wood Thrush too. Turns out there is just something beyond magical about a rainy hike where you’re basically serenaded by these the entire time. It’s also quite amazing how species can be found in basically the same exact spot each year: the phoebes at their nest, the Cerulean warbler in its stand of old growth along the first forested section and, best of all, the Indigo Bunting singing at the Cats Rock overlook. The only birds we really missed out on were the bobolinks in the field, though these are always a rare treat anyways. Speaking of Indigo Buntings, we’d like to extend a special thank you to the male who decided to break out in song 5 seconds into me proposing to Emily (also shoutout to the Prairie Warbler whose singing was also a constant presence there too). He was exactly where I hoped he would be and made the most amazing day all that more special. No new lifers today, but we’re both thrilled to be spending the rest of our lives together.

Checklist Comments: Felt like kind of a slow day based on the prime weather conditions, but also didn’t get to complete a loop of the island either. Highlights were the gregarious Fish Crows making mischief across the ballfields, haranguing starlings and poking into the lights on the fields. Also it was wonderful to get close looks at the Warbling Vireos in the freshwater wetlands.

Went from visitor center to east pond, southwest to northwest corner, then back along the fire road. Amazing day of birding with huge numbers of sandpipers far beyond our identification abilities. Probably some uncommon or rares even scattered among the least and semipalmated. Sadly there also were a large number of injured birds too, mostly with injured or missing legs. Dipped on the avocet but got to see plenty of other outstanding birds. Conditions were muddy but still easily passable.

Checklist Comments: Traveled from NE corner along hell gate and stopped checklist after abandoned golf driving range. Driving range was spectacular: abundant sparrows (5 species) all actively foraging and calling. Water was a little slower than expected but got to see a kestrel make a very lazy pass at a chickadee.

A really delightful winter day at Randall’s. Went from NE corner along kill and then finished at old golf range. Plentiful flocks of geese, gulls and shovelers along the NE corner. Finally made some progress on my gull ID by picking out an immature GBBG from afar. Highlight of the day was far and away the lifer Greater Scaup hanging out with an equally cute bufflehead in the western end of the Bronx kill. We ended up calling things short as the wind and chill were starting to get to us, but not before we had sparrow redemption with confident sightings of field sparrows (which we had mistaken a chipping sparrow for on our last visit). I had been very much hoping for an American tree sparrow too which all too briefly popped out at the very end. Only major dip was on the local kestrel(s) which we had hopped to catch up with.
dope Randall's day with Mr Meadows!

Walked from parking lot to tip of breezy point. Really outstanding first time visit to this spot. The first part of the walk was abundant with winter species, and the beach was covered in gulls and snow buntings. We got very lucky to run into tripper with the buntings who then pointed out the Lapland longspur and Iceland gull to us! A million thanks to you, Peter!

Checklist Comments: A really delightful winter day at Randall’s. Went from NE corner along kill and then finished at old golf range. Plentiful flocks of geese, gulls and shovelers along the NE corner. Finally made some progress on my gull ID by picking out an immature GBBG from afar. Highlight of the day was far and away the lifer Greater Scaup hanging out with an equally cute bufflehead in the western end of the Bronx kill. We ended up calling things short as the wind and chill were starting to get to us, but not before we had sparrow redemption with confident sightings of field sparrows (which we had mistaken a chipping sparrow for on our last visit). I had been very much hoping for an American tree sparrow too which all too briefly popped out at the very end. Only major dip was on the local kestrel(s) which we had hopped to catch up with.
dope Randall's day with Mr Meadows!
Walked from southeast corner to pedestrian bridge. Pretty quiet, but great FOS Brant sighting and possibly the largest RTHA we’ve ever seen.

Walked from parking lot to tip of breezy point. Really outstanding first time visit to this spot. The first part of the walk was abundant with winter species, and the beach was covered in gulls and snow buntings. We got very lucky to run into tripper with the buntings who then pointed out the Lapland longspur and Iceland gull to us! A million thanks to you, Peter!

Checklist Comments: Traveled from NE corner along hell gate and stopped checklist after abandoned golf driving range. Driving range was spectacular: abundant sparrows (5 species) all actively foraging and calling. Water was a little slower than expected but got to see a kestrel make a very lazy pass at a chickadee.
Salt marsh, freshwater meadow, down to southeast corner. Pretty quiet in the first 2 locations other than one active flock of chickadees.
dope Randall's day with Mr Meadows!

Felt like kind of a slow day based on the prime weather conditions, but also didn’t get to complete a loop of the island either. Highlights were the gregarious Fish Crows making mischief across the ballfields, haranguing starlings and poking into the lights on the fields. Also it was wonderful to get close looks at the Warbling Vireos in the freshwater wetlands.
Walked from southeast corner to pedestrian bridge. Pretty quiet, but great FOS Brant sighting and possibly the largest RTHA we’ve ever seen.

Walked from parking lot to tip of breezy point. Really outstanding first time visit to this spot. The first part of the walk was abundant with winter species, and the beach was covered in gulls and snow buntings. We got very lucky to run into tripper with the buntings who then pointed out the Lapland longspur and Iceland gull to us! A million thanks to you, Peter!

Checklist Comments: Went from visitor center to east pond, southwest to northwest corner, then back along the fire road. Amazing day of birding with huge numbers of sandpipers far beyond our identification abilities. Probably some uncommon or rares even scattered among the least and semipalmated. Sadly there also were a large number of injured birds too, mostly with injured or missing legs. Dipped on the avocet but got to see plenty of other outstanding birds. Conditions were muddy but still easily passable.

We were fully intending to get up and out the door asap for our first day of birding, and our only full one at that. Checklist Comments: We were pulling into Tupper Lake for the first night and were looking out over the lake when we spotted a rather large bucket out on the lake. We thought it must be some abandoned ice fishing apparatus until suddenly a white head appeared showing it to actually be an adult Bald Eagle! The eagle was feeding on an apparent fox carcass about 100 feet out on the lake. We got fantastic, grisly views of the bird feeding as light fell. What a great first bird of the trip!

Location: CHM Centro Habitat Mediterraneo LIPU Ostia

Observation Details: Male

Checklist Comments: Probably gotta be the best checklist and best trip we’ve done on the AT. Conditions were arguably poor, but I have to say a rainy hike has its own magic. I’ve never experienced the trail more birdy than this. From the moment we started to when we stopped we were surrounded by constant song and activity. The rain did nothing to dampen the songs and busy activity of summer. Willow flycatchers, yellow warblers and red-winged blackbirds were abundant along the boardwalk. An eastern phoebe pair again has set up shop at the end of the boardwalk. The woods were positively awash with song. The Ovenbird count is almost certainly a severe undercount as is the Veery and Wood Thrush too. Turns out there is just something beyond magical about a rainy hike where you’re basically serenaded by these the entire time. It’s also quite amazing how species can be found in basically the same exact spot each year: the phoebes at their nest, the Cerulean warbler in its stand of old growth along the first forested section and, best of all, the Indigo Bunting singing at the Cats Rock overlook. The only birds we really missed out on were the bobolinks in the field, though these are always a rare treat anyways. Speaking of Indigo Buntings, we’d like to extend a special thank you to the male who decided to break out in song 5 seconds into me proposing to Emily (also shoutout to the Prairie Warbler whose singing was also a constant presence there too). He was exactly where I hoped he would be and made the most amazing day all that more special. No new lifers today, but we’re both thrilled to be spending the rest of our lives together.

A really delightful winter day at Randall’s. Went from NE corner along kill and then finished at old golf range. Plentiful flocks of geese, gulls and shovelers along the NE corner. Finally made some progress on my gull ID by picking out an immature GBBG from afar. Highlight of the day was far and away the lifer Greater Scaup hanging out with an equally cute bufflehead in the western end of the Bronx kill. We ended up calling things short as the wind and chill were starting to get to us, but not before we had sparrow redemption with confident sightings of field sparrows (which we had mistaken a chipping sparrow for on our last visit). I had been very much hoping for an American tree sparrow too which all too briefly popped out at the very end. Only major dip was on the local kestrel(s) which we had hopped to catch up with.

Location: Bloomingdale Bog Trail--CR 55 to Bigelow Rd.
Checklist Comments: A truly lovely morning along the bog trail. Especially compared to the prior day’s snow wading, hiking along the trail was a breeze with frequent snowmobiles having compacted the snow nicely. We didn’t find the target Black-backed Woodpeckers, but still had an amazing time in the winter bog. We loved the two mail box feeders and their attendant Black-capped Chickadees, nuthatches and squirrels. We checked the dead snags along the trail but didn’t have sight or sound of the target rarity. A Hairy Woodpecker at the end certainly got our heart rate up, though!

Even though we had wonderful opportunistic sightings already, our first real target location of the trip was Sabbatis Bog. We had seen numerous reports in eBird and very helpful comments on the NY discord highly recommended a stop at the feeders on circle road. Nearly right after turning off the highway onto the road we were greeted by Red Crossbills. Even while driving, the bright flashes of red were unmistakeable! A bit further along, we neared the feeders and could see a flock of birds in the road. Approaching slowly we identified them as at least a dozen White-winged Crossbills pecking at the small bits of sand and gravel in the road. I love a good difficult chase as much as the next birder, but it’s also nice to get a trip started with a few of your targets sighted off the bat. We parked the car and started noting  and documenting the species at the feeders and also chatting with the incredibly friendly local birders too. The frequent crossbill sightings, chickadee dive bombs (I’m guessing our lack of outstretched hands of feed was drawing their ire) and nuthatch honking were more than enough for a very successful start to the trip! Then, as I was taking provably my 2,000th photo of a chickadee for the morning, Emily shouted and pointed to the top of one of the trees. Perched atop it was one of my 2 dream species for the trip: the pleasing grays, whites and blacks of a Canada Jay. This jay was quickly joined by another and set about hunting through the feeder options. The jays struck me with the apparent slowness of their flight (even more lackadaisical than their bluer cousins further south), and near total silence (completely unlike those rowdy cousins). I would have loved to linger even longer at the spot (and with hindsight… maybe we should have done so), but we were close to a possible spot for Boreal Chickadees so we ventured on.

Checklist Comments: Probably gotta be the best checklist and best trip we’ve done on the AT. Conditions were arguably poor, but I have to say a rainy hike has its own magic. I’ve never experienced the trail more birdy than this. From the moment we started to when we stopped we were surrounded by constant song and activity. The rain did nothing to dampen the songs and busy activity of summer. Willow flycatchers, yellow warblers and red-winged blackbirds were abundant along the boardwalk. An eastern phoebe pair again has set up shop at the end of the boardwalk. The woods were positively awash with song. The Ovenbird count is almost certainly a severe undercount as is the Veery and Wood Thrush too. Turns out there is just something beyond magical about a rainy hike where you’re basically serenaded by these the entire time. It’s also quite amazing how species can be found in basically the same exact spot each year: the phoebes at their nest, the Cerulean warbler in its stand of old growth along the first forested section and, best of all, the Indigo Bunting singing at the Cats Rock overlook. The only birds we really missed out on were the bobolinks in the field, though these are always a rare treat anyways. Speaking of Indigo Buntings, we’d like to extend a special thank you to the male who decided to break out in song 5 seconds into me proposing to Emily (also shoutout to the Prairie Warbler whose singing was also a constant presence there too). He was exactly where I hoped he would be and made the most amazing day all that more special. No new lifers today, but we’re both thrilled to be spending the rest of our lives together.

Location: Shindagin Hollow SF--Shindagin Hollow Rd. Wetland

Checklist Comments: After dipping on the BBWO north of the road, we decided to head south for some consolation feeder birds. We were more than adequately heartened by close encounters of the chickadee kind at the power line feeders. Then, right as we were getting ready to head back, the local corvid celebrities showed up and we were treated to some great views of 3 Canada Jays!

Even though we had wonderful opportunistic sightings already, our first real target location of the trip was Sabbatis Bog. We had seen numerous reports in eBird and very helpful comments on the NY discord highly recommended a stop at the feeders on circle road. Nearly right after turning off the highway onto the road we were greeted by Red Crossbills. Even while driving, the bright flashes of red were unmistakeable! A bit further along, we neared the feeders and could see a flock of birds in the road. Approaching slowly we identified them as at least a dozen White-winged Crossbills pecking at the small bits of sand and gravel in the road. I love a good difficult chase as much as the next birder, but it’s also nice to get a trip started with a few of your targets sighted off the bat. We parked the car and started noting  and documenting the species at the feeders and also chatting with the incredibly friendly local birders too. The frequent crossbill sightings, chickadee dive bombs (I’m guessing our lack of outstretched hands of feed was drawing their ire) and nuthatch honking were more than enough for a very successful start to the trip! Then, as I was taking provably my 2,000th photo of a chickadee for the morning, Emily shouted and pointed to the top of one of the trees. Perched atop it was one of my 2 dream species for the trip: the pleasing grays, whites and blacks of a Canada Jay. This jay was quickly joined by another and set about hunting through the feeder options. The jays struck me with the apparent slowness of their flight (even more lackadaisical than their bluer cousins further south), and near total silence (completely unlike those rowdy cousins). I would have loved to linger even longer at the spot (and with hindsight… maybe we should have done so), but we were close to a possible spot for Boreal Chickadees so we ventured on.

A really delightful winter day at Randall’s. Went from NE corner along kill and then finished at old golf range. Plentiful flocks of geese, gulls and shovelers along the NE corner. Finally made some progress on my gull ID by picking out an immature GBBG from afar. Highlight of the day was far and away the lifer Greater Scaup hanging out with an equally cute bufflehead in the western end of the Bronx kill. We ended up calling things short as the wind and chill were starting to get to us, but not before we had sparrow redemption with confident sightings of field sparrows (which we had mistaken a chipping sparrow for on our last visit). I had been very much hoping for an American tree sparrow too which all too briefly popped out at the very end. Only major dip was on the local kestrel(s) which we had hopped to catch up with.
dope Randall's day with Mr Meadows!

The rain did nothing to dampen the songs and busy activity of summer. Willow flycatchers, yellow warblers and red-winged blackbirds were abundant along the boardwalk. An eastern phoebe pair again has set up shop at the end of the boardwalk. The woods were positively awash with song. The Ovenbird count is almost certainly a severe undercount as is the Veery and Wood Thrush too. Turns out there is just something beyond magical about a rainy hike where you’re basically serenaded by these the entire time. It’s also quite amazing how species can be found in basically the same exact spot each year: the phoebes at their nest, the Cerulean warbler in its stand of old growth along the first forested section and, best of all, the Indigo Bunting singing at the Cats Rock overlook. The only birds we really missed out on were the bobolinks in the field, though these are always a rare treat anyways. Speaking of Indigo Buntings, we’d like to extend a special thank you to the male who decided to break out in song 5 seconds into me proposing to Emily (also shoutout to the Prairie Warbler whose singing was also a constant presence there too). He was exactly where I hoped he would be and made the most amazing day all that more special. No new lifers today, but we’re both thrilled to be spending the rest of our lives together.

Checklist Comments: A really delightful winter day at Randall’s. Went from NE corner along kill and then finished at old golf range. Plentiful flocks of geese, gulls and shovelers along the NE corner. Finally made some progress on my gull ID by picking out an immature GBBG from afar. Highlight of the day was far and away the lifer Greater Scaup hanging out with an equally cute bufflehead in the western end of the Bronx kill. We ended up calling things short as the wind and chill were starting to get to us, but not before we had sparrow redemption with confident sightings of field sparrows (which we had mistaken a chipping sparrow for on our last visit). I had been very much hoping for an American tree sparrow too which all too briefly popped out at the very end. Only major dip was on the local kestrel(s) which we had hopped to catch up with.
dope Randall's day with Mr Meadows!

Felt like kind of a slow day based on the prime weather conditions, but also didn’t get to complete a loop of the island either. Highlights were the gregarious Fish Crows making mischief across the ballfields, haranguing starlings and poking into the lights on the fields. Also it was wonderful to get close looks at the Warbling Vireos in the freshwater wetlands.

Location: Appalachian Trail (Dover Oak to Great Swamp CEA)

Checklist Comments: We were fully intending to get up and out the door asap for our first day of birding, and our only full one at that. However, when we went to take Wallace for his morning walk, we quickly realized we were actually already surrounded by birds! I’m thinking there must be a feeder nearby, since there was truly a shocking number of birds calling and foraging through the trees on the edge of the lake. The highlight had to be a resplendent bald eagle was saw flying along the far lake shore.

Even though we had wonderful opportunistic sightings already, our first real target location of the trip was Sabbatis Bog. We had seen numerous reports in eBird and very helpful comments on the NY discord highly recommended a stop at the feeders on circle road. Nearly right after turning off the highway onto the road we were greeted by Red Crossbills. Even while driving, the bright flashes of red were unmistakeable! A bit further along, we neared the feeders and could see a flock of birds in the road. Approaching slowly we identified them as at least a dozen White-winged Crossbills pecking at the small bits of sand and gravel in the road. I love a good difficult chase as much as the next birder, but it’s also nice to get a trip started with a few of your targets sighted off the bat. We parked the car and started noting  and documenting the species at the feeders and also chatting with the incredibly friendly local birders too. The frequent crossbill sightings, chickadee dive bombs (I’m guessing our lack of outstretched hands of feed was drawing their ire) and nuthatch honking were more than enough for a very successful start to the trip! Then, as I was taking provably my 2,000th photo of a chickadee for the morning, Emily shouted and pointed to the top of one of the trees. Perched atop it was one of my 2 dream species for the trip: the pleasing grays, whites and blacks of a Canada Jay. This jay was quickly joined by another and set about hunting through the feeder options. The jays struck me with the apparent slowness of their flight (even more lackadaisical than their bluer cousins further south), and near total silence (completely unlike those rowdy cousins). I would have loved to linger even longer at the spot (and with hindsight… maybe we should have done so), but we were close to a possible spot for Boreal Chickadees so we ventured on.

Observation Details: One heard and seen passing over prospect park.

Checklist Comments: Wandered around for an hour before finding the local celebrity woodpeckers. Ended up leading us to what has to be the coolest mixed flock of my life: pine warblers by the dozen, flashes of eastern bluebirds, brown headed nuthatches and red-cockaded woodpeckers squeezing their little lungs out. The colors and sounds made it feel like some sort of crazy southeastern pet store.  Top year and maybe life moment with the birds.

Wandered around for an hour before finding the local celebrity woodpeckers. Ended up leading us to what has to be the coolest mixed flock of my life: pine warblers by the dozen, flashes of eastern bluebirds, brown headed nuthatches and red-cockaded woodpeckers squeezing their little lungs out. The colors and sounds made it feel like some sort of crazy southeastern pet store.  Top year and maybe life moment with the birds.

After dipping on the BBWO north of the road, we decided to head south for some consolation feeder birds. We were more than adequately heartened by close encounters of the chickadee kind at the power line feeders. Then, right as we were getting ready to head back, the local corvid celebrities showed up and we were treated to some great views of 3 Canada Jays!

Location: Bloomingdale Bog Trail--CR 55 to Bigelow Rd.
Checklist Comments: A truly lovely morning along the bog trail. Especially compared to the prior day’s snow wading, hiking along the trail was a breeze with frequent snowmobiles having compacted the snow nicely. We didn’t find the target Black-backed Woodpeckers, but still had an amazing time in the winter bog. We loved the two mail box feeders and their attendant Black-capped Chickadees, nuthatches and squirrels. We checked the dead snags along the trail but didn’t have sight or sound of the target rarity. A Hairy Woodpecker at the end certainly got our heart rate up, though!

We were fully intending to get up and out the door asap for our first day of birding, and our only full one at that. However, when we went to take Wallace for his morning walk, we quickly realized we were actually already surrounded by birds! I’m thinking there must be a feeder nearby, since there was truly a shocking number of birds calling and foraging through the trees on the edge of the lake. The highlight had to be a resplendent bald eagle was saw flying along the far lake shore.

Even though we had wonderful opportunistic sightings already, our first real target location of the trip was Sabbatis Bog. We had seen numerous reports in eBird and very helpful comments on the NY discord highly recommended a stop at the feeders on circle road. Nearly right after turning off the highway onto the road we were greeted by Red Crossbills. Even while driving, the bright flashes of red were unmistakeable! A bit further along, we neared the feeders and could see a flock of birds in the road. Approaching slowly we identified them as at least a dozen White-winged Crossbills pecking at the small bits of sand and gravel in the road. I love a good difficult chase as much as the next birder, but it’s also nice to get a trip started with a few of your targets sighted off the bat. We parked the car and started noting  and documenting the species at the feeders and also chatting with the incredibly friendly local birders too. The frequent crossbill sightings, chickadee dive bombs (I’m guessing our lack of outstretched hands of feed was drawing their ire) and nuthatch honking were more than enough for a very successful start to the trip! Then, as I was taking provably my 2,000th photo of a chickadee for the morning, Emily shouted and pointed to the top of one of the trees. Perched atop it was one of my 2 dream species for the trip: the pleasing grays, whites and blacks of a Canada Jay. This jay was quickly joined by another and set about hunting through the feeder options. The jays struck me with the apparent slowness of their flight (even more lackadaisical than their bluer cousins further south), and near total silence (completely unlike those rowdy cousins). I would have loved to linger even longer at the spot (and with hindsight… maybe we should have done so), but we were close to a possible spot for Boreal Chickadees so we ventured on.

Observation Details: Heard

Checklist Comments: Probably gotta be the best checklist and best trip we’ve done on the AT. Conditions were arguably poor, but I have to say a rainy hike has its own magic. I’ve never experienced the trail more birdy than this. From the moment we started to when we stopped we were surrounded by constant song and activity. The rain did nothing to dampen the songs and busy activity of summer. Willow flycatchers, yellow warblers and red-winged blackbirds were abundant along the boardwalk. An eastern phoebe pair again has set up shop at the end of the boardwalk. The woods were positively awash with song. The Ovenbird count is almost certainly a severe undercount as is the Veery and Wood Thrush too. Turns out there is just something beyond magical about a rainy hike where you’re basically serenaded by these the entire time. It’s also quite amazing how species can be found in basically the same exact spot each year: the phoebes at their nest, the Cerulean warbler in its stand of old growth along the first forested section and, best of all, the Indigo Bunting singing at the Cats Rock overlook. The only birds we really missed out on were the bobolinks in the field, though these are always a rare treat anyways. Speaking of Indigo Buntings, we’d like to extend a special thank you to the male who decided to break out in song 5 seconds into me proposing to Emily (also shoutout to the Prairie Warbler whose singing was also a constant presence there too). He was exactly where I hoped he would be and made the most amazing day all that more special. No new lifers today, but we’re both thrilled to be spending the rest of our lives together.

A really delightful winter day at Randall’s. Went from NE corner along kill and then finished at old golf range. Plentiful flocks of geese, gulls and shovelers along the NE corner. Finally made some progress on my gull ID by picking out an immature GBBG from afar. Highlight of the day was far and away the lifer Greater Scaup hanging out with an equally cute bufflehead in the western end of the Bronx kill. We ended up calling things short as the wind and chill were starting to get to us, but not before we had sparrow redemption with confident sightings of field sparrows (which we had mistaken a chipping sparrow for on our last visit). I had been very much hoping for an American tree sparrow too which all too briefly popped out at the very end. Only major dip was on the local kestrel(s) which we had hopped to catch up with.
dope Randall's day with Mr Meadows!

Felt like kind of a slow day based on the prime weather conditions, but also didn’t get to complete a loop of the island either. Highlights were the gregarious Fish Crows making mischief across the ballfields, haranguing starlings and poking into the lights on the fields. Also it was wonderful to get close looks at the Warbling Vireos in the freshwater wetlands.

A really delightful winter day at Randall’s. Went from NE corner along kill and then finished at old golf range. Plentiful flocks of geese, gulls and shovelers along the NE corner. Finally made some progress on my gull ID by picking out an immature GBBG from afar. Highlight of the day was far and away the lifer Greater Scaup hanging out with an equally cute bufflehead in the western end of the Bronx kill. We ended up calling things short as the wind and chill were starting to get to us, but not before we had sparrow redemption with confident sightings of field sparrows (which we had mistaken a chipping sparrow for on our last visit). I had been very much hoping for an American tree sparrow too which all too briefly popped out at the very end. Only major dip was on the local kestrel(s) which we had hopped to catch up with.
dope Randall's day with Mr Meadows!

Also it was wonderful to get close looks at the Warbling Vireos in the freshwater wetlands.

Location: CHM Centro Habitat Mediterraneo LIPU Ostia

Checklist Comments: Probably gotta be the best checklist and best trip we’ve done on the AT. Conditions were arguably poor, but I have to say a rainy hike has its own magic. I’ve never experienced the trail more birdy than this. From the moment we started to when we stopped we were surrounded by constant song and activity. The rain did nothing to dampen the songs and busy activity of summer. Willow flycatchers, yellow warblers and red-winged blackbirds were abundant along the boardwalk. An eastern phoebe pair again has set up shop at the end of the boardwalk. The woods were positively awash with song. The Ovenbird count is almost certainly a severe undercount as is the Veery and Wood Thrush too. Turns out there is just something beyond magical about a rainy hike where you’re basically serenaded by these the entire time. It’s also quite amazing how species can be found in basically the same exact spot each year: the phoebes at their nest, the Cerulean warbler in its stand of old growth along the first forested section and, best of all, the Indigo Bunting singing at the Cats Rock overlook. The only birds we really missed out on were the bobolinks in the field, though these are always a rare treat anyways. Speaking of Indigo Buntings, we’d like to extend a special thank you to the male who decided to break out in song 5 seconds into me proposing to Emily (also shoutout to the Prairie Warbler whose singing was also a constant presence there too). He was exactly where I hoped he would be and made the most amazing day all that more special. No new lifers today, but we’re both thrilled to be spending the rest of our lives together.

Location: Larrabee State Park -- Clayton Beach Parking Area

Checklist Comments: Even though we had wonderful opportunistic sightings already, our first real target location of the trip was Sabbatis Bog. We had seen numerous reports in eBird and very helpful comments on the NY discord highly recommended a stop at the feeders on circle road. Nearly right after turning off the highway onto the road we were greeted by Red Crossbills. Even while driving, the bright flashes of red were unmistakeable! A bit further along, we neared the feeders and could see a flock of birds in the road. Approaching slowly we identified them as at least a dozen White-winged Crossbills pecking at the small bits of sand and gravel in the road. I love a good difficult chase as much as the next birder, but it’s also nice to get a trip started with a few of your targets sighted off the bat. We parked the car and started noting  and documenting the species at the feeders and also chatting with the incredibly friendly local birders too. The frequent crossbill sightings, chickadee dive bombs (I’m guessing our lack of outstretched hands of feed was drawing their ire) and nuthatch honking were more than enough for a very successful start to the trip! Then, as I was taking provably my 2,000th photo of a chickadee for the morning, Emily shouted and pointed to the top of one of the trees. Perched atop it was one of my 2 dream species for the trip: the pleasing grays, whites and blacks of a Canada Jay. This jay was quickly joined by another and set about hunting through the feeder options. The jays struck me with the apparent slowness of their flight (even more lackadaisical than their bluer cousins further south), and near total silence (completely unlike those rowdy cousins). I would have loved to linger even longer at the spot (and with hindsight… maybe we should have done so), but we were close to a possible spot for Boreal Chickadees so we ventured on.

Checklist Comments: We made an early drive out to Blue Ridge road to look for Boreal Chickadees. Thanks so very much to everyone from the NY discord for the tips on where to look, especially Jay! We stopped in about 4 different places on the road and listened for the chickadees. There were plentiful black-capped happily foraging and calling among the trees. We heard a few passing red-breasted nuthatches too and even got to lay eyes on a goldfinch for a bit. All in all not a bad morning even if we did dip on the target species. The dawn drive from tupper lake was gorgeous and we saw many a flock of crossbills gritting along the road. Hopefully we’ll get another shot at the boreals either on this trip or on a future one!

We were fully intending to get up and out the door asap for our first day of birding, and our only full one at that. However, when we went to take Wallace for his morning walk, we quickly realized we were actually already surrounded by birds! I’m thinking there must be a feeder nearby, since there was truly a shocking number of birds calling and foraging through the trees on the edge of the lake. The highlight had to be a resplendent bald eagle was saw flying along the far lake shore.

Checklist Comments: After dipping on the BBWO north of the road, we decided to head south for some consolation feeder birds. We were more than adequately heartened by close encounters of the chickadee kind at the power line feeders. Then, right as we were getting ready to head back, the local corvid celebrities showed up and we were treated to some great views of 3 Canada Jays!

Even though we had wonderful opportunistic sightings already, our first real target location of the trip was Sabbatis Bog. We had seen numerous reports in eBird and very helpful comments on the NY discord highly recommended a stop at the feeders on circle road. Nearly right after turning off the highway onto the road we were greeted by Red Crossbills. Even while driving, the bright flashes of red were unmistakeable! A bit further along, we neared the feeders and could see a flock of birds in the road. Approaching slowly we identified them as at least a dozen White-winged Crossbills pecking at the small bits of sand and gravel in the road. I love a good difficult chase as much as the next birder, but it’s also nice to get a trip started with a few of your targets sighted off the bat. We parked the car and started noting  and documenting the species at the feeders and also chatting with the incredibly friendly local birders too. The frequent crossbill sightings, chickadee dive bombs (I’m guessing our lack of outstretched hands of feed was drawing their ire) and nuthatch honking were more than enough for a very successful start to the trip! Then, as I was taking provably my 2,000th photo of a chickadee for the morning, Emily shouted and pointed to the top of one of the trees. Perched atop it was one of my 2 dream species for the trip: the pleasing grays, whites and blacks of a Canada Jay. This jay was quickly joined by another and set about hunting through the feeder options. The jays struck me with the apparent slowness of their flight (even more lackadaisical than their bluer cousins further south), and near total silence (completely unlike those rowdy cousins). I would have loved to linger even longer at the spot (and with hindsight… maybe we should have done so), but we were close to a possible spot for Boreal Chickadees so we ventured on.

Checklist Comments: Probably gotta be the best checklist and best trip we’ve done on the AT. Conditions were arguably poor, but I have to say a rainy hike has its own magic. I’ve never experienced the trail more birdy than this. From the moment we started to when we stopped we were surrounded by constant song and activity. The rain did nothing to dampen the songs and busy activity of summer. Willow flycatchers, yellow warblers and red-winged blackbirds were abundant along the boardwalk. An eastern phoebe pair again has set up shop at the end of the boardwalk. The woods were positively awash with song. The Ovenbird count is almost certainly a severe undercount as is the Veery and Wood Thrush too. Turns out there is just something beyond magical about a rainy hike where you’re basically serenaded by these the entire time. It’s also quite amazing how species can be found in basically the same exact spot each year: the phoebes at their nest, the Cerulean warbler in its stand of old growth along the first forested section and, best of all, the Indigo Bunting singing at the Cats Rock overlook. The only birds we really missed out on were the bobolinks in the field, though these are always a rare treat anyways. Speaking of Indigo Buntings, we’d like to extend a special thank you to the male who decided to break out in song 5 seconds into me proposing to Emily (also shoutout to the Prairie Warbler whose singing was also a constant presence there too). He was exactly where I hoped he would be and made the most amazing day all that more special. No new lifers today, but we’re both thrilled to be spending the rest of our lives together.

Checklist Comments: Probably gotta be the best checklist and best trip we’ve done on the AT. Conditions were arguably poor, but I have to say a rainy hike has its own magic. I’ve never experienced the trail more birdy than this. From the moment we started to when we stopped we were surrounded by constant song and activity. The rain did nothing to dampen the songs and busy activity of summer. Willow flycatchers, yellow warblers and red-winged blackbirds were abundant along the boardwalk. An eastern phoebe pair again has set up shop at the end of the boardwalk. The woods were positively awash with song. The Ovenbird count is almost certainly a severe undercount as is the Veery and Wood Thrush too. Turns out there is just something beyond magical about a rainy hike where you’re basically serenaded by these the entire time. It’s also quite amazing how species can be found in basically the same exact spot each year: the phoebes at their nest, the Cerulean warbler in its stand of old growth along the first forested section and, best of all, the Indigo Bunting singing at the Cats Rock overlook. The only birds we really missed out on were the bobolinks in the field, though these are always a rare treat anyways. Speaking of Indigo Buntings, we’d like to extend a special thank you to the male who decided to break out in song 5 seconds into me proposing to Emily (also shoutout to the Prairie Warbler whose singing was also a constant presence there too). He was exactly where I hoped he would be and made the most amazing day all that more special. No new lifers today, but we’re both thrilled to be spending the rest of our lives together.

Checklist Comments: Traveled from NE corner along hell gate and stopped checklist after abandoned golf driving range. Driving range was spectacular: abundant sparrows (5 species) all actively foraging and calling. Water was a little slower than expected but got to see a kestrel make a very lazy pass at a chickadee.

Wandered around for an hour before finding the local celebrity woodpeckers. Ended up leading us to what has to be the coolest mixed flock of my life: pine warblers by the dozen, flashes of eastern bluebirds, brown headed nuthatches and red-cockaded woodpeckers squeezing their little lungs out. The colors and sounds made it feel like some sort of crazy southeastern pet store.  Top year and maybe life moment with the birds.

Observation Details: Seen briefly in abandoned driving range  (40.7982871, -73.9252575). Don’t have photos but ID was very clear with dark grey upper parts, white under parts with prominent touch of yellow at shoulders. Seen moving with mixed flock of sparrows.
Checklist Comments: A really delightful winter day at Randall’s. Went from NE corner along kill and then finished at old golf range. Plentiful flocks of geese, gulls and shovelers along the NE corner. Finally made some progress on my gull ID by picking out an immature GBBG from afar. Highlight of the day was far and away the lifer Greater Scaup hanging out with an equally cute bufflehead in the western end of the Bronx kill. We ended up calling things short as the wind and chill were starting to get to us, but not before we had sparrow redemption with confident sightings of field sparrows (which we had mistaken a chipping sparrow for on our last visit). I had been very much hoping for an American tree sparrow too which all too briefly popped out at the very end. Only major dip was on the local kestrel(s) which we had hopped to catch up with.

Walked from parking lot to tip of breezy point. Really outstanding first time visit to this spot. The first part of the walk was abundant with winter species, and the beach was covered in gulls and snow buntings. Also it was wonderful to get close looks at the Warbling Vireos in the freshwater wetlands.

Location: Suttle Lake Lodge--Cinder Beach Day Use Area

Checklist Comments: Probably gotta be the best checklist and best trip we’ve done on the AT. Conditions were arguably poor, but I have to say a rainy hike has its own magic. I’ve never experienced the trail more birdy than this. From the moment we started to when we stopped we were surrounded by constant song and activity. The rain did nothing to dampen the songs and busy activity of summer. Willow flycatchers, yellow warblers and red-winged blackbirds were abundant along the boardwalk. An eastern phoebe pair again has set up shop at the end of the boardwalk. The woods were positively awash with song. The Ovenbird count is almost certainly a severe undercount as is the Veery and Wood Thrush too. Turns out there is just something beyond magical about a rainy hike where you’re basically serenaded by these the entire time. It’s also quite amazing how species can be found in basically the same exact spot each year: the phoebes at their nest, the Cerulean warbler in its stand of old growth along the first forested section and, best of all, the Indigo Bunting singing at the Cats Rock overlook. The only birds we really missed out on were the bobolinks in the field, though these are always a rare treat anyways. Speaking of Indigo Buntings, we’d like to extend a special thank you to the male who decided to break out in song 5 seconds into me proposing to Emily (also shoutout to the Prairie Warbler whose singing was also a constant presence there too). He was exactly where I hoped he would be and made the most amazing day all that more special. No new lifers today, but we’re both thrilled to be spending the rest of our lives together.

Checklist Comments: Wandered around for an hour before finding the local celebrity woodpeckers. Ended up leading us to what has to be the coolest mixed flock of my life: pine warblers by the dozen, flashes of eastern bluebirds, brown headed nuthatches and red-cockaded woodpeckers squeezing their little lungs out. The colors and sounds made it feel like some sort of crazy southeastern pet store.  Top year and maybe life moment with the birds.

Location: Hudson River Park--Tribeca Upland (Chambers to W Houston St.)

Checklist Comments: Traveled from NE corner along hell gate and stopped checklist after abandoned golf driving range. Driving range was spectacular: abundant sparrows (5 species) all actively foraging and calling. Water was a little slower than expected but got to see a kestrel make a very lazy pass at a chickadee.
Salt marsh, freshwater meadow, down to southeast corner. Pretty quiet in the first 2 locations other than one active flock of chickadees.

A really delightful winter day at Randall’s. Went from NE corner along kill and then finished at old golf range. Plentiful flocks of geese, gulls and shovelers along the NE corner. Finally made some progress on my gull ID by picking out an immature GBBG from afar. Highlight of the day was far and away the lifer Greater Scaup hanging out with an equally cute bufflehead in the western end of the Bronx kill. We ended up calling things short as the wind and chill were starting to get to us, but not before we had sparrow redemption with confident sightings of field sparrows (which we had mistaken a chipping sparrow for on our last visit). I had been very much hoping for an American tree sparrow too which all too briefly popped out at the very end. Only major dip was on the local kestrel(s) which we had hopped to catch up with.

Felt like kind of a slow day based on the prime weather conditions, but also didn’t get to complete a loop of the island either. Went from visitor center to east pond, southwest to northwest corner, then back along the fire road. Amazing day of birding with huge numbers of sandpipers far beyond our identification abilities. Probably some uncommon or rares even scattered among the least and semipalmated. Sadly there also were a large number of injured birds too, mostly with injured or missing legs. Dipped on the avocet but got to see plenty of other outstanding birds. Conditions were muddy but still easily passable.
